		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/07/09/business/09db-euro-web1-LN/09db-euro-web1-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/07/09/business/09db-euro-web1-LN/09db-euro-web1-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/07/09/business/09db-euro-web1-LN/09db-euro-web1-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003812162" width="592" height="395" alt="A nut and herbs seller in a market in central Athens. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2015/07/09/business/dealbook/greek-debt-dispute-highlights-prospect-of-a-euro-exit.html&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">A nut and herbs seller in a market in central Athens. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/07/09/business/dealbook/greek-debt-dispute-highlights-prospect-of-a-euro-exit.html">Related Article</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Eirini Vourloumis for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/07/21/summer-reading-contest-winner-week-4-the-greek-economic-crisis-and-why-americans-should-care/" data-title="Summer Reading Contest Winner, Week 4 | The Greek Economic Crisis and Why Americans Should Care" data-description="One winner, 7 runners-up, and 25 honorable mentions. Thank you for participating, and remember to post every week until Aug. 21 at 7 a.m.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><webonly><span id="t10h2s" class="update">Update, Aug. 24 | If you were a winner, runner-up or honorable mention in this contest anytime this summer, we have a <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/08/24/the-learning-network-student-council-an-opportunity-for-students-honored-in-our-summer-reading-contest/">special opportunity for you</a>. </span></webonly></p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/07/03/summer-reading-contest-week-4-what-interested-you-most-in-the-times-this-week">Week 4</a> of our <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/05/07/the-sixth-annual-new-york-times-summer-reading-contest/">Summer Reading Contest</a>, we were impressed by the many students who contemplated headline news &#8212; whether the Pluto flyby or the removal of the Confederate battle flag from the South Carolina State House &#8212; and speculated about what it might mean for the future.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/07/03/summer-reading-contest-week-4-what-interested-you-most-in-the-times-this-week/?comments#permid=15417842">mckinzieadmiralsH2015</a> wrote, for example: &#8220;What was once a moving, pixelated dot, will become a real world with complexity and diversity. All the pictures that we have in our heads of what Pluto looks like will be replaced with reality.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Our favorite this week, however, was a post by<strong> <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/07/03/summer-reading-contest-week-4-what-interested-you-most-in-the-times-this-week/?comments#permid=15446035">ElenaPRHSLions2015</a></strong> that takes Americans to task for what she sees as mistaken assumptions about Greece and its economic crisis.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Thank you for participating, and congratulations if you are one of the many honored below. And don&#8217;t forget: You can post an <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/05/07/the-sixth-annual-new-york-times-summer-reading-contest/">entry</a> every week until Aug. 21 at 7 a.m.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-160005"></span></p>
<hr />
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Winner</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">By <strong><a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/07/03/summer-reading-contest-week-4-what-interested-you-most-in-the-times-this-week/?comments#permid=15446035">ElenaPRHSLions2015</a></strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It is easy for people living in an economically privileged country to adopt a âwhy should we careâ attitude about the economic crisis in Greece. It is doubly simple to shovel the responsibility of debt onto a âlazyâ population of Greek people, leaving corrupt political institutions (who made the decisions to encourage stifling neoliberal policies) with little dirt to dust off their shoulders.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">America is steeped in Greek culture. We commercialize Greek mythology, commodify Greek ideas, popularize Greek philosophy. We treat the Greek vacation islands like they&#8217;re representative of all of Greece, as if solidarity tourism was a way of âhelping out the Greek economyâ and not a play into the fallacy of trickle-down economics that only helps the rich get richer.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While we bolster our media and market with appropriation of Greek culture, we are selectively ignoring the part of that culture where Greeks were working the third-longest number of hours in the world and still being labeled as âlazy,â where there has been a 272 percent increase in depression due to poor living conditions, where the rich can demand austerity to solve the problems they created at the expense of the poor. But as the article states, Greeks do not want more austerity measures; the vote for a leftist government was also a vote against debt slavery under the E.U. Awareness of the Greek crisis is more important than ever as the fight to improve Greek economy and living conditions continues.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/07/09/business/dealbook/greek-debt-dispute-highlights-prospect-of-a-euro-exit.html">Euro, Envisioned as Force for Unity, Becomes Weapon in Greek Crisis</a>&#8221;</p>
<hr />
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Runners-Up</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/07/03/summer-reading-contest-week-4-what-interested-you-most-in-the-times-this-week/?comments#permid=15412337">KylieCHSGoBlue15</a> on the vanishing tradition of keeping ticket stubs</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/07/03/summer-reading-contest-week-4-what-interested-you-most-in-the-times-this-week/?comments#permid=15419759">LeahMCHS2015</a> on the Confederate flag</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/07/03/summer-reading-contest-week-4-what-interested-you-most-in-the-times-this-week/?comments#permid=15397451">AnnaJLENICK2015</a> on shark attacks</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/07/03/summer-reading-contest-week-4-what-interested-you-most-in-the-times-this-week/?comments#permid=15445520">Cameron C APE199</a> on women and apologies</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/07/03/summer-reading-contest-week-4-what-interested-you-most-in-the-times-this-week/?comments#permid=15442381">JacksonARITCHEY</a> on the movie &#8220;Inside Out&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/07/03/summer-reading-contest-week-4-what-interested-you-most-in-the-times-this-week/?comments#permid=15431699">JulieHuskieHonors11</a> on the wage gap in professional sports</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/07/03/summer-reading-contest-week-4-what-interested-you-most-in-the-times-this-week/?comments#permid=15417842">mckinzieadmiralsH2015</a> on Pluto</p>
<hr />
